[[div class="blockquote"]]
**K1337 Meeting Room, Site-37 Aboveground Premises**
@@@@
**13-09-2024T09:00:00 PST**

An abridged transcript is shown below. To download the full 2 hour, 44 minute recording, open this document with the [[span style="font-family:'Cascadia Code'"]]-verbose[[/span]] flag. 

----

//13 Foundation and Taut employees are seated around a conference table, making small talk. A few employees are attending the meeting via video conferencing software, and their 3D digital avatars are displayed on a large monitor covering a wall of the room.//

**Thompson:** Happy Friday everyone! Looks like we're all here. Shall we get started?

**Gilbert:**  I'll run the random number generator...aaanddd it's Lague! You're up first.

//A few moments pass.//

**Thompson:** Lague, you might be on m-

**SCP-XXXX-0070:**[[footnote]]The anomality of SCP-XXXX instances was not known at the time.[[/footnote]] Sorry, was on mute. Looks like my coffee hasn't kicked in yet haha!

//Most people in the room lightly chuckle. A few digital avatars emote a laughing gesture.//

**SCP-XXXX-0134:** Maybe we should call you Jet Lague from now on!

//Most people in the room lightly chuckle. A few digital avatars emote a laughing gesture.//

**SCP-XXXX-0070:** Yeah, haha. Site-82's on the other side of the planet. As most of you know, I'm placed on secondment over here.

**Gilbert**: Those folks treating you alright?

**SCP-XXXX-0070:** They're fine...just a bit backwards. I'll be restructuring their task allocation framework into a pre-planned execution, with integrated management processes and streamlined oversight. Into something like what we have here.

**Thompson:** Have you run into any blockers?

**SCP-XXXX-0070:** Just the usual red tape we expect from this place. I can use our success here at Solving Computer Problems as a sample case study to push for the restructure.

**Thompson:** Sounds like a swell plan Lague!

**SCP-XXXX-0070:** Any time, Thompson.

**Thompson:** Cool, let's move on. Give it another spin Gilbert.

//21 minutes of fluff omitted.//

**Carnegie:** I just got back from leave, so not much from me. I'll look through our inventory and pick up something simple to warm up.

**Thompson:** Just FYI, we've just updated our login protocols, courtesy of Taut. So ping me if you run into trouble.

**Gilbert:** Alrighty...next is...me! Just working on a couple of laptops we received the other day. So far they're all mundane.

**SCP-XXXX-0070:** Did you filter them through our Hume detectors?

**Gilbert:** Yeah. The Grade III ones. They sit in the acceptable bounds with an error margin of ±0.0001. I also ran through the standard workflow diagnostics and all seem fi-

**SCP-XXXX-0134:** Bump the detectors to Grade IV. Can never be too careful.

**Gilbert**: Oh? I didn't know we had any detectors stronger than Grade III.

**Thompson:** Must be those experimental ones Director Lague mentioned the other day?

**SCP-XXXX-0134:** Indeed. Gotta keep with the times, Gilbert.

**Gilbert:** Do we have any in stock? I've only found II's and III's in the equipment lockers.

**SCP-XXXX-0134:** I'll pull some strings and get some sent over[[footnote]]MTF Foobar intercepted a Taut delivery a week after the incident, and the suspect 'Grade IV' detectors are jailbroken Grade I detectors which artificially increase detected Hume values by random minute values.[[/footnote]]. Don't you worry your little head.

**Gilbert:** Uhh, sure.

**SCP-XXXX-0070:**

**SCP-XXXX-0134:** Now that's an idea.

**Thompson:** You're on fire today Lague!

//34 minutes of fluff omitted.//

**Colliers:** So, average runbook adherence is down 8.6% from last week. Maybe we should loosen the runbook requirements to give the frontline staff a bit more flexibility to-

**SCP-XXXX-0134:** A better idea would be to up the incentives a bit more.

**SCP-XXXX-0070:** Currently runbook adherence is a metric for team performance. If we tie it to individual performance instead, it'd be possible to influence their bonus payout.

**Thompson:** Yeah, I'll schedule a meeting to look at rebalancing the department's remuneration calculation.

**Colliers:** So we're not adjusting the runbook? Some customers have been complaining, which makes the guidelines a little difficult to follow.

**SCP-XXXX-0134:** This runbook was designed by Taut's Customer Experience team. It's used by several of our Fortune 500 partners.

**SCP-XXXX-0070:** It's important that we stick to the runbook and ensure a consistent experience for all our customers.

**Thompson:** Very important.

**SCP-XXXX-0070:** But if you have any concerns, Ms. Colliers, we're happy for you to join the meeting that Thompson has very nicely decided to schedule for us.

**Colliers:** O-of course, director.

**Thompson:** Now last but not least, I believe we have a new guy joining us today.

**Gilbert:** Why don't you introduce yourself Farleigh?

**Farleigh:** Hey all, I'm-

**Thompson:** New girl, sorry! Looks like my coffee hasn't kicked in either haha!

//Most people in the room lightly chuckle. A few digital avatars emote a laughing gesture.//

**Farleigh:** ...I'm Marina Farleigh. Rotating from Site 45 to join Site-37 HR as an analyst.

**SCP-XXXX-0134:** Human resources! One of my favourite departments.

//Farleigh and a few other engineers in the room chuckle, but stifle their laughter when the others don't join in.//

**Farleigh:** Anyway, if someone could show me the HR workstations, I'll be happy to get started and hit the ground running. I've already done my prework for this facility.

**SCP-XXXX-0070:** You're doing well as a PO, Thompson.



**SCP-XXXX-0445:** Grabbing your coffee's important, but punctuality is even more important. Let's remember that for tomorrow, hm?

